profile: The Apollo Community has the most centrally located residence halls on campus. It is comprised of four two-story buildings with suite-style floor plans, in which four or five residents occupy the suite. Each suite is made up of two or three rooms, a bathroom and a common living space. The shared common living room area comes unfurnished so students can use the space in many different ways. Each of the four residence halls has a lounge area, laundry room, and vending machines.
name: Apollo Community

profile: The UCF Arboretum is an outdoor laboratory that supports and encourages relevant, experience-based learning, urban ecology research, and fosters human connections with ecosystems and landscapes. The Arboretum contributes to student development and engagement through volunteer, service-learning and educational opportunities. It is one of the many ways in which UCF engages with the community - providing partnership and outreach initiatives that increase awareness and understanding of key issues in ecology, natural resource conservation, and urban horticulture. While the focus is on the Central Florida region, our diverse, inclusive program supports global efforts to create sustainable urban environments around the world.
title: Arboretum (ARB)

profile: The Duke Energy Welcome Center, formerly known as the Progress Energy Welcome Center, is home to the Office of Undergraduate Admissions. The 19,000-square-foot, $4.4 million center opened in August 2004. The center welcomes 30,000 guests from all over the world each year. Other organizations that use the facility are the Department of Child, Family and Community Sciences, the Community Counseling Clinic, the Department of Educational and Human Sciences, the School of Teaching, Learning and Leadership and the Toni Jennings Exceptional Education Institute.

profile: The general classroom building's name was changed to Howard Phillips Hall after an Orlando businessman and entrepreneur made significant contributions to the university. Howard Phillips Hall holds more offices and departments than it does classrooms. Notably, First Year Advising and Exploration (FYAE), University Testing Center and Student Academic Resource Center (SARC) are located in the basement. These programs offer resources for students including advising, testing help and tutoring for classes. The departments of anthropology, political science and sociology are also located in Howard Phillips Hall. Additionally, more resources for students can be found in the offices of Transfer and Transition Services, Upward Bound, Multicultural Academic & Support Services, Metropolitan Center for Regional Studies, Global Perspectives and UCF Faculty Senate Office.

profile:
The John T. Washington Center with its signature covered breezeway offers students and visitors shopping, dining, banking and student services. It is centrally located on UCF's main campus between the Student Union and The John C. Hitt Library. The John T. Washington Center averages 35,000 to 40,000 visitors per day. Tenants include UCF Barnes & Noble Bookstore, Chick-fil-A, UCF Card Services, FAIRWINDS Credit Union, The Spot Print & Ship Store, CFE Credit Union, UCF Victim Services, Skateboards & Sports, A-1 Hair Studio, and In Style Women's Boutique.

Built in 1979, this 40,000 square foot building was the original Student Union. It was later named after Dr. John T. Washington, an Associate Professor of Sociology who passed away in 1983. The renaming of the structure was a tribute to his university and community accomplishments.

Address: 101 to 115 Aquarius Agora Dr. Orlando, Florida 32816

profile: The Knights Helping Knights Pantry began from a class project in a first year LEAD Scholars course in 2009. UCF students wanted to create a food pantry where fellow students would have access to free necessities if they fell on hard times. This grass roots initiative strived to ensure that UCF students would not have to choose between buying text books or buying groceries. Since its inception, the Knights Helping Knights Pantry has expanded from a closet at the Student Union to its own suite located in Ferrell Commons attached to the All Knight Study facility.
title: Knight's Pantry
name: Knight's Pantry

profile:
The Libra Community features six residence halls housing approximately 1000 students who are mostly in their first-year at UCF. The Libra Community is close to the Health Center, dining hall, and Recreation and Wellness Center. There are two different styles of rooms in the community, although both are four person suites with two double occupancy bedrooms that share a common bathroom.

In the center of the community is the Libra Community Center, a common area with a large screen television, used for area residential programming and student use. There is also a common kitchen area that students may use by request of the residence life staff. There are also two laundry rooms and an area for vending machines. Students can park with a student decal in the South parking garage or surface lots located near the community.
name: Libra Community

profile: Completed in 2007, the 74,250 square-feet Psychology Building is home to the psychology department and the philosophy department, and the Learning Institute For Elders (LIFE). The psychology department is one of the largest College of Science programs with over 2,900 majors and 650 minors. The psychology building provides a centralized structure to house the psychology department's primary responsibilities of teaching, student research, and corporate research partnerships. The building includes classrooms, a teaching laboratory, study spaces, several research laboratories, offices and academic support. In addition, the psychology building houses a clinic that focuses on behavioral approaches to therapy without prescribing medication. The clinic serves the community by providing free treatment for individuals with social phobia through the National Institute of Mental Health program.

profile: Robinson Observatory was built in 1994 and 1995, and dedicated on April 25, 1996. Astronomy outreach, education and research has gone on at the observatory ever since. The observatory is named for one of UCF's Founders, Herbert O. Robinson, who provided much of the funds necessary for the building's construction. The efforts of the Central Florida Astronomical Society, a local amateur astronomy group, were vital in initiating the idea of a UCF campus observatory, in seeing the project to its fruition and in finding a telescope to be housed under the dome. The observatory is currently run by the Department of Physics with the help of the Astronomy Society at UCF, a campus RSO.

Food locations include Asian Chao, Balagan, Corner Café, Domino's Pizza, Greens Salad Bar, Huey Magoo's Express, Joffrey's Coffee, Knightstop, Mrs. Field's Bakery, Nathan's Famous Hot Dogs, Qdoba Mexican Grill, Smoothie King, Subway, Topper's Creamery and Wackadoo's Grub and Brew. Offices include, Activity & Service Fee Business Office, Multicultural Academic & Support Services, Multicultural Student Center, Office of Student Involvement, Pride Commons, SDES Community Support Services, Student Government Association and Student Leadership Development.

profile: The $11 million Teaching Academy opened in September 2003 to prepare educators for excellence in education, lifelong learning and partnership. The offices are located on the fourth floor, where there are more than 50 work stations. The College of Education and Human Performance facility is equipped to accommodate about 7,000 students. One notable program, named after a former state senator, the Toni Jennings Exceptional Educational Institute, was created to develop educational opportunities and support for children and adults with special needs. Several other programs reside within the Teaching Academy, but two stand out in excellence; the Lockheed Martin/UCF Academy for Mathematics and Science.

profile: The Towers at Knight Plaza feature 11.5 month agreements for fall, spring, and summer beginning each fall. These apartments feature kitchens with dishwashers, single bedrooms with full-size beds and optional parking. The typical apartment layout has four bedrooms sharing two bathrooms. The Towers are located next to the UCF Arena, the Bright House Networks Stadium, restaurants, and retail shops. The Towers are a perfect option for first-year students who want their own room. Students living in the Towers range from first-year to graduate students. You are encouraged to apply early since the Towers are a very popular housing option.

profile: Located on the north side of campus, VAB is the home of the School of Visual Arts and Design (SVAD). SVAD offers the Art B.A. concentrations of Art History, Books Arts, Ceramics, Drawing and Printmaking, Illustration, Painting, Sculpture, and Type and Design, as well as B.F.A. programs in Emerging Media: Graphic Design and Experimental Animation tracks, and B.F.A. programs in Studio Art. With two floors and 68,921 square feet, it has ample space for art studios, classrooms and large lecture halls, as well as wall space for displaying artwork. The VAB also houses the UCF Art Gallery and a 454-seat auditorium.
